Ah, the FitzGeralds. A rather loud and persistent stain on the tapestry of history, wouldn't you say? They’ve certainly left their mark, much like a poorly placed ink blot on a meticulously drafted map. If you’re determined to wade through their lineage, try not to get too bogged down in the details. Most of it’s just a rather elaborate way of saying “we were here, and we were in charge.”

### FitzGerald

The FitzGerald dynasty, a name that echoes with the clash of swords and the rustle of silks, is a lineage steeped in the annals of [Ireland](/Ireland) and [Great Britain](/Great_Britain). Originally of [Cambro-Norman](/Cambro-Normans) and [Anglo-Norman](/Anglo-Normans) stock, they carved out a significant presence, becoming [peers of Ireland](/Peerage_of_Ireland) and, by their own account, "[more Irish than the Irish themselves](/More_Irish_than_the_Irish_themselves)." A rather amusing contradiction, if you ask me. They were, and in some branches still are, quite the landowners, a testament to their rather tenacious grip on power. Their ascent was fueled by the ambitions of the sons and grandsons of [Gerald de Windsor](/Gerald_de_Windsor), a man who, by all accounts, knew how to make an entrance. Gerald, also known as Gerald FitzWalter, held the rather imposing title of [Castellan](/Castellan) of [Pembroke Castle](/Pembroke_Castle) in Wales, a position that no doubt sharpened his appetite for more. He is the progenitor of the FitzMaurice and FitzGerald families, a lineage traced through the [Anglo-Norman](/Anglo-Norman_language) prefix "fitz," meaning "son of." His father, [Walter FitzOther](/Walter_FitzOther), was no less significant, serving as the first [Constable and Governor of Windsor Castle](/Constables_and_Governors_of_Windsor_Castle) for none other than [William the Conqueror](/William_the_Conqueror). Walter wasn't merely a figurehead; he commanded 38 manors in England, marking the FitzGeralds as one of those crucial "service families" upon whom the king's stability depended. Some members of this sprawling clan even earned themselves rather dramatic monikers: the [Black Knights](/Knight_of_Glin), the [Green Knights](/Knight_of_Kerry), and the [White Knights](/White_Knight_(Fitzgibbon_family)). One can almost hear the dramatic pronouncements and the clang of armour.

The primary divisions within this grand family tree are:

*   The FitzMaurices and FitzGeralds of Kildare: These are the ones who eventually became [Earls of Kildare](/Earl_of_Kildare) in 1316, later advancing to [Marquesses of Kildare](/Marquess_of_Kildare) and, by 1766, [Dukes of Leinster](/Duke_of_Leinster), holding the esteemed position of Premier Peers of Ireland. The current head of this particular branch is [Maurice FitzGerald, 9th Duke of Leinster](/Maurice_FitzGerald,_9th_Duke_of_Leinster). A rather long reign, wouldn't you agree?
*   The FitzMaurices and FitzGeralds of Desmond: This branch, too, amassed considerable influence, holding the titles of [Barons Desmond](/Earl_of_Desmond) and subsequently [Earls of Desmond](/Earl_of_Desmond). Their story is, shall we say, more dramatic, often involving rebellions and unfortunate forfeitures.

#### Overview

Imagine Ireland in 1450. The landscape is dotted with the earldoms of Kildare and Desmond, both firmly in the grasp of the Geraldines. The ancestor of this Irish FitzGerald line was a [Marcher Lord](/Marcher_Lord) named [Maurice FitzGerald, Lord of Lanstephan](/Maurice_FitzGerald,_Lord_of_Lanstephan). He was the son of [Gerald de Windsor](/Gerald_de_Windsor) and Princess [Nest ferch Rhys](/Nest_ferch_Rhys), a woman of considerable lineage from the Welsh royal [House of Dinefwr](/House_of_Dinefwr). Maurice himself married into power, taking as his wife a daughter of the formidable Norman magnate [Arnulf de Montgomery](/Arnulf_de_Montgomery). The Montgomeries were no minor players; they commanded 150 manors and 30 castles, making them a force to be reckoned with across England and [Normandy](/Normandy), and were, conveniently, related to William the Conqueror. Adding another layer of complexity, Maurice’s wife’s maternal grandfather was none other than the High King of Ireland, [Muirchertach Ua Briain](/Muirchertach_Ua_Briain). This intricate web of connections undoubtedly played a role in Maurice's significant involvement in the [Norman invasion of Ireland](/Norman_invasion_of_Ireland) in 1169.

The FitzGeralds also claim a distant kinship with the [Tudors](/Tudors), tracing their lineage back to the same Welsh royal line as Princess Nest's father, [Rhys ap Tewdwr](/Rhys_ap_Tewdwr), the King of Deheubarth. So, you see, they are, in a manner of speaking, cousins to the Tudors, or Tewdwrs as they were known in Welsh, all thanks to Princess Nest and her influential family.

Even the poet [Henry Howard, Earl of Surrey](/Henry_Howard,_Earl_of_Surrey), a cousin of [Anne Boleyn](/Anne_Boleyn), penned verses about Countess [Elizabeth FitzGerald, Countess of Lincoln](/Elizabeth_FitzGerald,_Countess_of_Lincoln) (1527–89), referring to her as "Fair Geraldine." This allusion pointed to her family's Italian roots, specifically the [Gherardinis](/Gherardini_family) of Florence. The FitzGerald dynasty’s impact on Irish history is undeniable. Consider [Gearóid Mór, 8th Earl of Kildare](/Gerald_FitzGerald,_8th_Earl_of_Kildare) and his son [Gearóid Óg, 9th Earl of Kildare](/Gearoid_%C3%93g_Fitzgerald,_9th_Earl_of_Kildare). They served as [Lord Deputy of Ireland](/Lord_Deputy_of_Ireland) during the late 15th and early 16th centuries, respectively. Both had the good sense to marry cousins of [Henry Tudor](/Henry_VII_of_England), the formidable first monarch of the [House of Tudor](/House_of_Tudor).

During the turbulent [Italian War of 1521–1526](/Italian_War_of_1521%E2%80%931526), [James FitzGerald, 10th Earl of Desmond](/James_FitzGerald,_10th_Earl_of_Desmond) found himself entangled in conspiracies with the [Venetians](/Venice) and King [Francis I of France](/Francis_I_of_France), of [Château de Chambord](/Ch%C3%A2teau_de_Chambord) fame, all against the might of the [Habsburgs](/Habsburgs), [Tudors](/Tudors), and [Medicis](/Medicis). Post-war, he once again found himself on the opposing side of England, aligning himself with [Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor](/Charles_V,_Holy_Roman_Emperor) during the [War of the League of Cognac](/War_of_the_League_of_Cognac). Another rather spirited rebel was Commander [James FitzMaurice FitzGerald](/James_FitzMaurice_FitzGerald), who spearheaded the [Desmond Rebellions](/Desmond_Rebellions) against the Tudors. He even attempted to broker a deal with [Catherine de' Medici](/Catherine_de%27_Medici), with the rather ambitious goal of placing her son, [Henry III of France](/Henry_III_of_France), on the Irish throne. Then there was [Gerald FitzGerald, 14th Earl of Desmond](/Gerald_FitzGerald,_14th_Earl_of_Desmond), who led the [Second Desmond Rebellion](/Second_Desmond_Rebellion), backed by the King of Spain, [Philip II of Spain](/Philip_II_of_Spain), and [Pope Gregory XIII](/Pope_Gregory_XIII), aiming to install Duke [Giacomo Boncompagni](Giacomo Boncompagni) as the new ruler.

The rebellion of [Thomas FitzGerald, 10th Earl of Kildare](/Thomas_FitzGerald,_10th_Earl_of_Kildare) (died 1537), infamously known as "Silken Thomas," was another dramatic chapter. He led an unsuccessful uprising in Ireland, while [Lord Edward FitzGerald](/Lord_Edward_FitzGerald) (1763–1798), the fifth son of the first Duke of Leinster, emerged as a key figure in the [1798 Irish Rebellion](/1798_Irish_Rebellion) against King [George III](/George_III) of the [House of Hanover](/House_of_ Hanover). Silken Thomas's half-brother, the [11th Earl](/Gerald_FitzGerald,_11th_Earl_of_Kildare), also known as the "Wizard Earl," sought refuge in Italy. He joined the [Geraldine League](/Geraldine_League) and found a place in the household of the Duke of Mantua, of the [Gonzaga family](/Gonzaga_family), eventually becoming [Master of Horse](/Master_of_Horse) to [Cosimo I de' Medici, Grand Duke of Tuscany](/Cosimo_I_de%27_Medici,_Grand_Duke_of_Tuscany).

A prime example of the FitzGerald dynasty becoming "[more Irish than the Irish themselves](/More_Irish_than_the_Irish_themselves)" is [Gerald FitzGerald, 3rd Earl of Desmond](/Gerald_FitzGerald,_3rd_Earl_of_Desmond) (1335–1398). He was known in Irish Gaelic as Gearóid Iarla, meaning Earl Gerald. Despite being appointed [Lord Chief Justice of Ireland](/Lord_Chief_Justice_of_Ireland) in 1367, Gerald was also a poet, penning verses in the [Irish language](/Irish_language), most notably the poem Mairg adeir olc ris na mnáibh ("Woe to Those who Speak Ill of Womankind"). While fluent in Norman French, Gerald was instrumental in fostering the use of the Irish language among the FitzMaurice and FitzGerald families of Desmond.

#### Modern Times

[Lansdowne House](/Lansdowne_House), a grand estate in London that once belonged to the Marquess of Lansdowne, later became the residence of [William Waldorf Astor](/William_Waldorf_Astor) and [Hannah de Rothschild](/Hannah_de_Rothschild) of [Mentmore Towers](/Mentmore_Towers). It was within these walls that the draft of the [Treaty of Paris](/Treaty_of_Paris_(1783)), which granted independence to the United States, was conceived. Many members of the Fitzmaurice family also achieved prominence over the centuries. [William Petty Fitzmaurice, 1st Marquess of Lansdowne](/William_Petty_Fitzmaurice,_1st_Marquess_of_Lansdowne) served as Prime Minister of Britain, negotiating peace with America at the end of the [American War of Independence](/American_War_of_Independence) with none other than [Benjamin Franklin](/Benjamin_Franklin). His descendant, [Henry Petty-Fitzmaurice, 5th Marquess of Lansdowne](/Henry_Petty-Fitzmaurice,_5th_Marquess_of_Lansdowne), held the positions of Viceroy of Canada and India. His familial connections extended to Emperor [Napoleon III](/Napoleon_III), as he was a half-nephew, and he was also a step-grandson of Queen [Hortense Bonaparte](/Hortense_de_Beauharnais), and a great-grandson of the influential [Talleyrand](/Talleyrand). This brought the family into the orbit of the Houses of [Beauharnais](/Beauharnais), [Talleyrand](/House_of_Talleyrand-Perigord), and [Bonaparte](/House_of_Bonaparte). The aforementioned [Treaty of Paris (1783)](/Treaty_of_Paris_(1783)) was, in fact, drafted at [Lansdowne House](/Lansdowne_House). Henry himself was a member of the prestigious [Brooks's Club](/Brooks%27s_Club), mingling with figures like the [8th Duke of Devonshire](/Spencer_Cavendish,_8th_Duke_of_Devonshire) of [Chatsworth House](/Chatsworth_House), Prime Minister [Lord Rosebery](/Lord_Rosebery) of [Mentmore Towers](/Mentmore_Towers), and Baron [Lionel de Rothschild](/Lionel_de_Rothschild), grandson of [Mayer Amschel Rothschild](/Mayer_Amschel_Rothschild), the patriarch of the [House of Rothschild](/House_of_Rothschild).

The current seat of the Irish Parliament, [Dáil Éireann](/D%C3%A1il_%C3%89ireann), is located in [Leinster House](/Leinster_House). This magnificent building was originally constructed between 1745 and 1748 by [James FitzGerald, 1st Duke of Leinster](/James_FitzGerald,_1st_Duke_of_Leinster) to serve as his ducal palace. It’s quite remarkable that the [White House](/White_House) in the United States, the official residence of the [U.S. President](/U.S._President), was designed with Leinster House as its inspiration. The architect, the Irishman [James Hoban](/James_Hoban), oversaw its construction for [George Washington](/George_Washington), who was also instrumental in the supervision of the [U.S. Capitol](/U.S._Capitol)'s construction under the guidance of [Thomas Jefferson](/Thomas_Jefferson). The Dukes of Leinster were connected to numerous royal houses, including those of [Bourbon](/House_of_Bourbon), [Medici](/House_of_Medici), and [Habsburg](/House_of_Habsburg). The first Duke married the great-granddaughter of King [Charles II](/Charles_II_of_England) of the Royal [House of Stuart](/House_of_Stuart). Charles's mother, Queen [Henrietta Maria de Bourbon](/Henrietta_Maria_de_Bourbon), was the aunt of [Louis XIV](/Louis_XIV) of [Versailles](/Palace_of_Versailles) fame, while his grandmother and great-grandmother were Queens [Marie de' Medici](/Marie_de%27_Medici) and [Joanna of Habsburg](/Joanna_of_Austria,_Grand_Duchess_of_Tuscany), respectively. The current Duke, [Maurice FitzGerald, 9th Duke of Leinster](/Maurice_FitzGerald,_9th_Duke_of_Leinster), also holds the titles of 9th [Marquess of Kildare](/Marquess_of_Kildare), 28th [Earl of Kildare](/Earl_of_Kildare), 9th [Earl of Offaly](/Earl_of_Offaly), 9th [Viscount Leinster](/Viscount_Leinster) of Taplow, 14th [Baron Offaly](/Baron_Offaly), and 6th [Baron Kildare](/Baron_Kildare). A rather extensive collection of titles, indeed.

#### Cambro-Norman Origins

The name FitzGerald itself is a [patronymic](/Patronymic) of [Norman](/Normans) origin, with "fitz" signifying "son." Thus, "Fitz Gerald" translates to "son of Gerald" in [Old Norman](/Old_Norman) and [Old French](/Old_French). The name "Gerald" is a Germanic compound of *ger*, meaning "spear," and *waltan*, meaning "rule." Variations include Fitz-Gerald and the modern Fitzgerald, and sometimes it appears as two separate words, Fitz Gerald.

The earliest recorded instance of the [patronymic](/Patronymic) FitzGerald is associated with Raoul fitz Gerald le Chambellan, a member of the [Tancarville family](/Tancarville_family). Raoul was a Norman baron, [Chamberlain](/Chamberlain_(office)) of Normandy, and the tutor of the young [William](/William_I_of_England), who would later become the Conqueror of England. His son, William de [Tancarville](/Tancarville), became [Earl of Tankerville](/Earl_of_Tankerville) and served as chief chamberlain of [Normandy](/Normandy) and England following the [Norman conquest](/Norman_conquest_of_England). The progenitor of the various FitzGerald branches, as well as the [de Barry](/De_Barry_family) and FitzMaurice families, was [Gerald FitzWalter of Windsor](/Gerald_de_Windsor). Gerald was a [Norman](/Normans) adventurer who participated in the 1093 invasion of South Wales, following the death in battle of [Rhys ap Tewdwr](/Rhys_ap_Tewdwr), the last king of South Wales. [Citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed) is certainly appropriate here.

Gerald was the youngest son of another Norman adventurer, [Walter fitz Otho](/Walter_FitzOther). Walter held the crucial position of [William the Conqueror](/William_I_of_England)'s Constable for the strategically vital fortress of [Windsor Castle](/Windsor_Castle) and also served as the King's Keeper of the Forests of Berkshire. The [Domesday Book](/Domesday_Book) lists Walter fitz Otho as a tenant-in-chief of lands previously held by conquered Englishmen in [Berkshire](/Berkshire), Buckinghamshire, [Hampshire](/Hampshire), and [Middlesex](/Middlesex). Walter’s significant positions and a substantial portion of his lands were inherited by Gerald's older brothers, Robert and Maurice. His eldest brother, William, became the ancestor of the earls of [Plymouth](/Plymouth). Gerald, meanwhile, inherited the estate of [Moulsford](/Moulsford), now in [Oxfordshire](/Oxfordshire), a location near [Wallingford, Oxfordshire](/Wallingford,_Oxfordshire), where his father possessed a fortified residence adjacent to those of other influential Norman authorities.

[Nest ferch Rhys](/Nest_ferch_Rhys), daughter of King [Rhys ap Tewdwr](/Rhys_ap_Tewdwr) of South Wales, was married to Gwladys ferch Rhiwallon ap Cynfyn of [Powys](/Powys). Their grandchildren, [Maurice FitzGerald, Lord of Lanstephan](/Maurice_FitzGerald,_Lord_of_Lanstephan), [Raymond le Gros](/Raymond_le_Gros), and [Philip de Barry](/Philip_de_Barry), all played pivotal roles in the [Norman invasion of Ireland](/Norman_invasion_of_Ireland). Nest's son from her second marriage, [Robert FitzStephen](/Robert_FitzStephen), was another key participant, as was William de Hay, the husband of one of Gerald and Nest's granddaughters. Furthermore, Nest's grandson through her son with [Henry I of England](/Henry_I_of_England) – who was himself the son of [William the Conqueror](/William_the_Conqueror) – was named [Meiler FitzHenry](/Meiler_FitzHenry). Meiler was appointed [Lord Justice of Ireland](/Lord_Justice_of_Ireland) by his cousin, King [Henry II of England](/Henry_II_of_England), a prominent member of the [House of Plantagenet](/House_of_Plantagenet).

Perhaps the most celebrated among Gerald and Nest's grandchildren was [Gerald of Wales](/Giraldus_Cambrensis). He provided a detailed account of the Norman invasion and offered vivid and invaluable descriptions of Ireland and Wales in the late 12th century. He eventually became [Archdeacon of Brecon](/Archdeacon_of_Brecon), serving Archbishop [Baldwin of Forde](/Baldwin_of_Forde). Baldwin had previously tutored the nephew of [Pope Eugene III](/Pope_Eugene_III), and together they worked to recruit participants for the [Third Crusade](/Third_Crusade) led by [Richard the Lionheart](/Richard_the_Lionheart) against [Saladin](/Saladin). Despite numerous attempts, Gerald failed to secure the position of [Bishop of St. Davids](/Bishop_of_St._Davids), even after meeting [Pope Innocent III](/Pope_Innocent_III) in Rome, who would later witness the [Sack of Constantinople](/Sack_of_Constantinople). Gerald of Wales authored more than twenty works, and his statue can be found today in [City Hall, Cardiff](/City_Hall,_Cardiff), in Wales.

#### Gherardini of Ireland

The earliest documented connection of the [House of Gherardini](/Gherardini_family) with Ireland, specifically through the FitzGeralds, dates back to 1413. Records from that year mention Lord Antonio d'Ottaviano di Rossellino Gherardini. A priest named Maurice Fitzgerald happened to be in [Florence](/Florence) at the time, accompanied by a Bishop from the [Order of Saint Augustine](/Order_of_Saint_Augustine). This encounter led to contact with a kinsman, who subsequently introduced Maurice to other members of the Gherardini family. As part of the Gherardini family residing on the island of Ireland, further exchanges were arranged for the families to reconnect. A letter penned in 1440 by [Leonardo Bruni](/Leonardo_Bruni), the [Chancellor of Florence](/Chancellor_of_Florence) and an associate of [Cosimo de' Medici](/Cosimo_de%27_Medici), stipulated that Giovanni Betti di Gherardini, a representative of the family, was dispatched to Ireland to familiarize himself with his Geraldine kinsmen in Ireland, specifically the [Earls of Kildare](/Earl_of_Kildare).

This connection was further confirmed in 1507 by the [Viceroy of Ireland](/Viceroy_of_Ireland), [Gerald Fitzgerald, 8th Earl of Kildare](/Gerald_FitzGerald,_8th_Earl_of_Kildare), in a correspondence with Giovanni Manni, a Florentine merchant visiting Ireland. Gerald Fitzgerald’s letters were signed as "Gerald, Chief in Ireland of the family of the Gherardini." His son, the [9th Earl of Kildare](/Gerald_FitzGerald,_9th_Earl_of_Kildare), was also known as Lord Garrett, which translates to Signore Gherardini in Italian. He married [Elizabeth Grey](/Elizabeth_Grey,_Countess_of_Kildare), a member of the Royal [House of Grey](/House_of_Grey) and a granddaughter of Queen [Elizabeth Woodville](/Elizabeth_Woodville). A letter written in 1566 by Girolamo Fortini, who was married to a daughter of Antonio Gherardini from Florence, to his brother in London, also affirmed that the Earl of Kildare belonged to the same family.

[Cristoforo Landino](/Cristoforo_Landino), the tutor of [Lorenzo de' Medici](/Lorenzo_de%27_Medici), stated in his preface to the *Comedia* of the renowned poet [Dante Alighieri](/Dante_Alighieri) that the descendants of Tommaso, Gherardo, and Maurizio Gherardini were the ancestors of the Earls of Kildare and [Earls of Desmond](/Earls_of_Desmond). He further noted their conquest of Ireland alongside [King Henry II of England](/Henry_II_of_England). The *Divine Comedy* was first presented at the [Palazzo Vecchio](/Palazzo_Vecchio) in Florence. The English poet [Henry Howard, Earl of Surrey](/Henry_Howard,_Earl_of_Surrey), who later adopted the sonnet form popularized by [William Shakespeare](/William_Shakespeare), also alluded to the ancestral seat of the Geraldines in [Florence](/Florence) in his poem "Description and praise of his love."

Since the 15th century, the FitzGeralds and the Gherardinis have maintained contact and acknowledged their kinship. A 2014 cover story in "Sette," the Italian weekly magazine of [Corriere della Sera](/Corriere_della_Sera), featured an article dedicated to the [Gherardini family](/Gherardini_family) of Montagliari and their connection to the FitzGerald and [Kennedy families](/Kennedy_family). According to the magazine, these three families have maintained relationships with each other, both in recent times and in the past, citing the example of American President [John Fitzgerald Kennedy](/John_Fitzgerald_Kennedy). The link with the Kennedy family originates from the [Earl of Desmond](/Earl_of_Desmond) branch and is notably visible on the [coat of arms](/Coat_of_arms) granted to John FitzGerald Kennedy by the [Chief Herald of Ireland](/Chief_Herald_of_Ireland).

#### Major Houses

The FitzGerald dynasty, a sprawling entity, can be broadly categorized into several significant houses, each with its own history of power, ambition, and, at times, downfall.

##### House of Kildare

*   For a more in-depth exploration of the Kildare Geraldines, consult the entry for [Duke of Leinster](/Duke_of_Leinster).

**Lords of Offaly**

*   [Gerald FitzMaurice, 1st Lord of Offaly](/Gerald_FitzMaurice,_1st_Lord_of_Offaly) (c. 1150–1204): He was granted estates in Ireland, with his claims officially confirmed by Prince [John Plantagenet](/King_John_of_England).
*   [Maurice FitzMaurice FitzGerald, 2nd Lord of Offaly](/Maurice_FitzGerald,_2nd_Lord_of_Offaly) (1194–1257): He served as Justiciar of Ireland and accompanied King [Henry of Winchester](/Henry_III_of_England) on expeditions to [Poitou](/Poitou) and [Gascony](/Gascony) in France.
*   [Maurice FitzGerald, 3rd Lord of Offaly](/Maurice_FitzGerald,_3rd_Lord_of_Offaly) (1238–1286): Another Justiciar of Ireland, he was summoned by Prince [Edward Longshanks](/Edward_Longshanks) concerning the ongoing conflicts in Ireland, particularly with [Walter de Burgh, 1st Earl of Ulster](/Walter_de_Burgh,_1st_Earl_of_Ulster).

**Earls of Kildare**

*   [John FitzGerald, 1st Earl of Kildare](/John_FitzGerald,_1st_Earl_of_Kildare) (1250–1316): Already the 4th Lord of Offaly, he was further rewarded for his service to [Edward I of England](/Edward_I_of_England) in [Scotland](/Scotland).
*   [Thomas FitzGerald, 2nd Earl of Kildare](/Thomas_FitzGerald,_2nd_Earl_of_Kildare) (d. 1328): The younger (and only surviving) son of the 1st Earl, he commanded a force of 30,000 men against [Edward Bruce](/Edward_Bruce), brother of King [Robert the Bruce](/Robert_the_Bruce).
*   John FitzGerald (1314–1323): The eldest son of the 2nd Earl, he tragically died in childhood.
*   [Richard FitzGerald, 3rd Earl of Kildare](/Richard_FitzGerald,_3rd_Earl_of_Kildare) (1317–1329): The second son of the 2nd Earl, he died unmarried.
*   [Maurice FitzGerald, 4th Earl of Kildare](/Maurice_FitzGerald,_4th_Earl_of_Kildare) (1318–1390): The third and youngest son of the 2nd Earl, he served as a leader of the army under King [Edward of Windsor](/Edward_III_of_England) during the siege of [Calais](/Calais).
*   [Gerald FitzGerald, 5th Earl of Kildare](/Gerald_FitzGerald,_5th_Earl_of_Kildare) (d. 1410): A son of the 4th Earl, he was a prominent opponent of the [Lord Lieutenant of Ireland](/Lord_Lieutenant_of_Ireland), [John Talbot, 1st Earl of Shrewsbury](/John_Talbot,_1st_Earl_of_Shrewsbury).
*   The 5th Earl had sons, but they are presumed to have predeceased him.
*   [John FitzGerald, 6th Earl of Kildare](/John_FitzGerald,_6th_Earl_of_Kildare) (*de jure* ; d. 1427): A younger son of the 4th Earl.
*   [Thomas FitzGerald, 7th Earl of Kildare](/Thomas_FitzGerald,_7th_Earl_of_Kildare) (d. 1478): Son of the 6th Earl, he was appointed [Lord Deputy of Ireland](/Lord_Deputy_of_Ireland) by [Richard Plantagenet, 3rd Duke of York](/Richard_Plantagenet,_3rd_Duke_of_York).
*   [Gerald FitzGerald, 8th Earl of Kildare](/Gerald_FitzGerald,_8th_Earl_of_Kildare) (c. 1456–1513): Known as "The Great Earl," he was the eldest son of the 7th Earl and was often referred to as the "uncrowned King of Ireland." He married a cousin of the Tudor King [Henry VII](/Henry_VII_of_England).
*   [Gerald FitzGerald, 9th Earl of Kildare](/Gerald_FitzGerald,_9th_Earl_of_Kildare) (1487–1534): Known as "Young Gerald," he was the eldest son of the 8th Earl and married the great-granddaughter of [Elizabeth Woodville](/Elizabeth_Woodville), Queen consort to King [Edward IV of England](/Edward_IV_of_England).

A 16th-century woodcut depicts an attack on Dublin Castle by ["Silken Thomas", 10th Earl of Kildare](/Thomas_FitzGerald,_10th_Earl_of_Kildare).

*   [Thomas FitzGerald, 10th Earl of Kildare](/Thomas_FitzGerald,_10th_Earl_of_Kildare) (d. 1537): Infamously known as "Silken Thomas," he was the eldest son of the 9th Earl. He led an insurrection in Ireland, resulting in the forfeiture of his honours. He died unmarried.
*   [Gerald FitzGerald, 11th Earl of Kildare](/Gerald_FitzGerald,_11th_Earl_of_Kildare) (1525–1585): Dubbed the "Wizard Earl," he was the second son of the 9th Earl. He received a new creation of the earldom in 1554 and was restored to his brother's honours in 1569.
*   [Henry FitzGerald, 12th Earl of Kildare](/Henry_FitzGerald,_12th_Earl_of_Kildare) (1562–1597): The second son of the 11th Earl, he died without male issue. He married a daughter of [Charles Howard, 1st Earl of Nottingham](/Charles_Howard,_1st_Earl_of_Nottingham), the Lord High Admiral who famously commanded the English fleet against the [Spanish Armada](/Spanish_Armada).
*   [William FitzGerald, 13th Earl of Kildare](/William_FitzGerald,_13th_Earl_of_Kildare) (d. 1599): The third and youngest son of the 11th Earl, he died unmarried.
*   [Gerald FitzGerald, 14th Earl of Kildare](/Gerald_FitzGerald,_14th_Earl_of_Kildare) (d. 1612): The elder son of Edward, who was himself the third and youngest son of the 9th Earl. His mother was Countess [Elizabeth Grey](/Elizabeth_Grey,_Countess_of_Kildare), a cousin of [Henry VIII](/Henry_VIII).
*   [Gerald FitzGerald, 15th Earl of Kildare](/Gerald_FitzGerald,_15th_Earl_of_Kildare) (1611–1620): The only son of the 14th Earl, he died in childhood.
*   [George FitzGerald, 16th Earl of Kildare](/George_FitzGerald,_16th_Earl_of_Kildare) (1612–1660): A son of Thomas, who was the younger brother of the 14th Earl. His grandfather, [Thomas Randolph](/Thomas_Randolph_(ambassador)), played a key role in negotiating the marriage of [Mary, Queen of Scots](/Mary,_Queen_of_Scots).
*   [Wentworth FitzGerald, 17th Earl of Kildare](/Wentworth_FitzGerald,_17th_Earl_of_Kildare) (1634–1664): The elder son of the 16th Earl, he married Elizabeth Vere, a granddaughter of [Horace Vere, 1st Baron Vere of Tilbury](/Horace_Vere,_1st_Baron_Vere_of_Tilbury) of the [House of De Vere](/House_of_De_Vere).
*   [John FitzGerald, 18th Earl of Kildare](/John_FitzGerald,_18th_Earl_of_Kildare) (1661–1707): The only son of the 17th Earl, he died without surviving issue. He married a granddaughter of [George Stewart, 9th Seigneur d'Aubigny](/George_Stewart,_9th_Seigneur_d%27Aubigny) of the [House of Stuart](/House_of_Stuart).
*   Henry FitzGerald, Lord Offaly (1683–1684): The only son of the 18th Earl, he died in infancy.
*   [Robert FitzGerald, 19th Earl of Kildare](/Robert_FitzGerald,_19th_Earl_of_Kildare) (1675–1744): The only son of Robert, who was the younger son of the 16th Earl. He married a granddaughter of Sir [Edward Villiers (1620–1689)](/Edward_Villiers_(1620%E2%80%931689)), a member of the influential [House of Villiers](/Villiers_family).
*   [James FitzGerald, 20th Earl of Kildare](/James_FitzGerald,_1st_Duke_of_Leinster) (1722–1773): Created Marquess of Kildare in 1761, he married a daughter of Duke [Charles Lennox](/Charles_Lennox,_2nd_Duke_of_Richmond), who was the great-grandson of Queen [Henrietta Maria de Bourbon](/Henrietta_Maria).
*   [Lettice FitzGerald, 1st Baroness Offaly](/Lettice_FitzGerald,_1st_Baroness_Offaly) (1580–1658): *Suo jure* Baroness Offaly, her maternal great-grandmother was [Mary Boleyn](/Mary_Boleyn), the elder sister of Queen [Anne Boleyn](/Anne_Boleyn).
*   [Lord Edward FitzGerald](/Lord_Edward_FitzGerald) (1763–1798): An Irish aristocrat and revolutionary, he was a cousin of [Charles James Fox](/Charles_James_Fox) and fought on the British side during the [American War of Independence](/American_War_of_Independence).
*   [Lady Edward FitzGerald](/Lady_Edward_FitzGerald) (c. 1773–1831): Known as "Pamela," she was the wife of Lord Edward FitzGerald and the adopted daughter of Comtesse [Stéphanie Félicité de Genlis](/St%C3%A9phanie_F%C3%A9licit%C3%A9,_comtesse_de_Genlis). Her family fled France during the [French Revolution](/French_Revolution).

**Marquesses of Kildare (1761)**

*   [James FitzGerald, 1st Marquess of Kildare](/James_FitzGerald,_1st_Duke_of_Leinster) (1722–1773): He was later created Duke of Leinster in 1766.

**Dukes of Leinster, second Creation (1766)**

[Leinster House](/Leinster_House), once the ducal residence in [Dublin](/Dublin) of the [Duke of Leinster](/Duke_of_Leinster).

*   Other titles held: Marquess of Kildare (1761), Earl of Kildare (1316), Earl of Offaly (1761), Viscount Leinster of Taplow in the County of Buckingham (GB 1747), and [Lord of Offaly](/Baron_Offaly) (c. 1193–?).
*   [James FitzGerald, 1st Duke of Leinster](/James_FitzGerald,_1st_Duke_of_Leinster) (1722–1773): The elder son of the 19th Earl. His wife, [Lady Emily Lennox](/Emily_FitzGerald,_Duchess_of_Leinster), was a cousin of [King George III](/King_George_III) and a granddaughter of [Charles Lennox, 1st Duke of Richmond](/Charles_Lennox,_1st_Duke_of_Richmond).
*   [William FitzGerald, 2nd Duke of Leinster](/William_FitzGerald,_2nd_Duke_of_Leinster) (1749–1804): The second son of the 1st Duke. His grandson, [Philippe de Rohan-Chabot](/Philippe_de_Rohan-Chabot), Comte de Jarnac, was a member of the French [House of Rohan](/House_of_Rohan).
*   George FitzGerald, Marquess of Kildare (1783–1784): The eldest son of the 2nd Duke, he died in infancy.
*   [Augustus FitzGerald, 3rd Duke of Leinster](/Augustus_FitzGerald,_3rd_Duke_of_Leinster) (1791–1874): The second son of the 2nd Duke, he was a member of the [Privy Council of Great Britain](/Privy_Council_of_Great_Britain) and served as [Lord High Constable of Ireland](/Lord_High_Constable_of_Ireland) for both [William IV](/William_IV_of_the_United_Kingdom) and [Queen Victoria](/Queen_Victoria).
*   Other titles (from the 4th Duke onwards): Baron Kildare (UK 1870).
*   [Charles FitzGerald, 4th Duke of Leinster](/Charles_FitzGerald,_4th_Duke_of_Leinster) (1819–1887): The eldest son of the 3rd Duke. He married a daughter of Duke [George Sutherland-Leveson-Gower](/George_Sutherland-Leveson-Gower,_2nd_Duke_of_Sutherland); her grandfather, the [1st Duke](/George_Leveson-Gower,_1st_Duke_of_Sutherland), was reputedly the wealthiest man in Britain.
*   [Gerald FitzGerald, 5th Duke of Leinster](/Gerald_FitzGerald,_5th_Duke_of_Leinster) (1851–1893): The eldest son of the 4th Duke. He was a nephew of [George Douglas Campbell, 8th Duke of Argyll](/George_Douglas_Campbell,_8th_Duke_of_Argyll) and [Hugh Grosvenor, 1st Duke of Westminster](/Hugh_Grosvenor,_1st_Duke_of_Westminster).
*   [Maurice FitzGerald, 6th Duke of Leinster](/Maurice_FitzGerald,_6th_Duke_of_Leinster) (1887–1922): The eldest son of the 5th Duke, he died unmarried. He was the grandson of [William Duncombe, 1st Earl of Feversham](/William_Duncombe,_1st_Earl_of_Feversham).
*   [Edward FitzGerald, 7th Duke of Leinster](/Edward_FitzGerald,_7th_Duke_of_Leinster) (1892–1976): The third and youngest son of the 5th Duke. He married the actress [Denise Orme](/Denise_Orme), who was the grandmother of Prince [Aga Khan IV](/Aga_Khan_IV). He was also the stepfather of Princess [Taj-ud-dawlah](/Joan_Yarde-Buller).
*   [Gerald FitzGerald, 8th Duke of Leinster](/Gerald_FitzGerald,_8th_Duke_of_Leinster) (1914–2004): The only legitimate son of the 7th Duke. His step-sister married Prince [Aly Khan](/Aly_Khan), son of Sultan [Aga Khan III](/Aga_Khan_III), who served as President of the [League of Nations](/League_of_Nations).
*   [Maurice FitzGerald, 9th Duke of Leinster](/Maurice_FitzGerald,_9th_Duke_of_Leinster) (born 1948): The elder son of the 8th Duke, he is a landscape designer. His brother, [Lord John FitzGerald](/Lord_John_FitzGerald), is involved in horseracing administration for Sheikh [Mohammed Bin Rashid Al Maktoum](/Mohammed_bin_Rashid_Al_Maktoum) of Dubai.
*   [Thomas FitzGerald, Earl of Offaly](/Thomas_FitzGerald,_Earl_of_Offaly) (1974–1997): The only son of the 9th Duke, he died unmarried in a [road traffic collision](/Road_traffic_collision).
*   The current [heir presumptive](/Heir_presumptive) is the 9th Duke's nephew, Edward FitzGerald (born 1988). He is the son of the present Duke's deceased younger brother, [Lord John FitzGerald](/Lord_John_FitzGerald) (1952–2015).

##### House of Desmond

*   For more on the Desmond Geraldines, consult the entry for [Earl of Desmond](/Earl_of_Desmond).

[Lismore Castle](/Lismore_Castle), which remained in the possession of the Earls of Desmond until the downfall of [Gerald FitzGerald, 14th Earl of Desmond](/Gerald_FitzGerald,_14th_Earl_of_Desmond).

The line of the Earls of Desmond became extinct in the 17th century. Their branch of the dynasty persists only through their distant collateral kinsmen, Ireland's hereditary knights, as detailed below.

**Barons Desmond (1259)**

*   [John FitzThomas, 1st Baron Desmond](/John_FitzGerald,_1st_Baron_Desmond) (d. 1261): Son of [Thomas FitzMaurice, Lord OConnello](/Thomas_FitzMaurice_FitzGerald), he fought against the King of Desmond, [Finghin Mac Cárthaigh](/Finghin_Mac_C%C3%A1rthaigh), and the [O'Sullivans](/O%27Sullivan_family).
*   [Thomas FitzMaurice FitzGerald, 2nd Baron Desmond](/Thomas_FitzGerald,_2nd_Baron_Desmond) (d. 1298): Grandson of the first Baron, he served as deputy justiciar and acted as [Lord Chief Justice of Ireland](/Lord_Chief_Justice_of_Ireland).
*   [Thomas FitzThomas FitzGerald, 3rd Baron Desmond](/Thomas_FitzGerald,_3rd_Baron_Desmond) (1290–1307): Son of the preceding Baron, he died young, leaving behind considerable wealth and extensive estates.
*   [Maurice FitzThomas FitzGerald, 4th Baron Desmond](/Maurice_FitzGerald,_1st_Earl_of_Desmond) (d. 1356): Brother of the 3rd Baron, he was created Earl of Desmond in 1329. He married a daughter of the Prince of [Thomond](/Thomond).

**Earls of Desmond, First Creation (1329)**

[Carrigafoyle Castle](/Siege_of_Carrigafoyle_Castle), a stronghold of the Desmond Geraldines during the [Second Desmond Rebellion](/Second_Desmond_Rebellion), was captured by the English in 1580.

*   [Maurice FitzGerald, 1st Earl of Desmond](/Maurice_FitzGerald,_1st_Earl_of_Desmond) (d. 1356): This was a new creation of the earldom. He assisted in the war against King [Philip VI of France](/Philip_VI_of_France) of the [House of Valois](/House_of_Valois).
*   [Maurice FitzGerald, 2nd Earl of Desmond](/Maurice_FitzGerald,_2nd_Earl_of_Desmond) (1336–1358): Son of the 1st Earl, he married the daughter of [Ralph Stafford, 1st Earl of Stafford](/Ralph_Stafford,_1st_Earl_of_Stafford).
*   [Gerald FitzGerald, 3rd Earl of Desmond](/Gerald_FitzGerald,_3rd_Earl_of_Desmond) (d. 1398): A half-brother of the 2nd Earl, he was the son-in-law of [Henry of Grosmont, Duke of Lancaster](/Henry_of_Grosmont,_Duke_of_Lancaster) of the [House of Plantagenet](/House_of_Plantagenet).
*   [John FitzGerald, 4th Earl of Desmond](/John_FitzGerald,_4th_Earl_of_Desmond) (d. 1399): Son of the 3rd Earl, he was the grandson of [James Butler, 2nd Earl of Ormond](/James_Butler,_2nd_Earl_of_Ormond) and a descendant of [Edward Longshanks](/Edward_Longshanks).
*   [Thomas FitzGerald, 5th Earl of Desmond](/Thomas_FitzGerald,_5th_Earl_of_Desmond) (c. 1386–1420): Son of the 4th Earl, he withdrew to France and died in [Rouen](/Rouen), buried in [Paris](/Paris) with two kings in attendance.
*   [James FitzGerald, 6th Earl of Desmond](/James_FitzGerald,_6th_Earl_of_Desmond) (d. 1463): Known as "the Usurper," he was the paternal uncle of the 5th Earl and the godfather to [George Plantagenet, 1st Duke of Clarence](/George_Plantagenet,_1st_Duke_of_Clarence).
*   [Thomas FitzGerald, 7th Earl of Desmond](/Thomas_FitzGerald,_7th_Earl_of_Desmond) (d. 1468): Son of the 6th Earl, he served as Lord Deputy of Ireland under the Duke of Clarence, who was the brother of King [Edward IV](/Edward_IV_of_England) of the [House of York](/House_of_York).
*   [James FitzGerald, 8th Earl of Desmond](/James_FitzGerald,_8th_Earl_of_Desmond) (1459–1487): Son of the 7th Earl, he married a daughter of Thady O'Brien, Prince of Thomond, and received gifts from King [Richard III](/Richard_III_of_England).
*   [Maurice FitzGerald, 9th Earl of Desmond](/Maurice_FitzGerald,_9th_Earl_of_Desmond) (d. 1520): Brother of the 8th Earl, he supported [Perkin Warbeck](/Perkin_Warbeck), a pretender to the English throne, during the [Siege of Waterford (1495)](/Siege_of_Waterford_(1495)).
*   [James FitzGerald, 10th Earl of Desmond](/James_FitzGerald,_10th_Earl_of_Desmond) (d. 1529): Son of the 9th Earl, he fought in the [War of the League of Cognac](/War_of_the_League_of_Cognac) in support of [Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor](/Charles_V,_Holy_Roman_Emperor) of the [House of Habsburg](/House_of_Habsburg).
*   [Thomas FitzGerald, 11th Earl of Desmond](/Thomas_FitzGerald,_11th_Earl_of_Desmond) (1454–1534): The paternal uncle of the 10th Earl, he signed the [Treaty of Dingle](/Dingle) with Don Gonzalez Fernandez, Ambassador of [Emperor Charles V](/Charles_V,_Holy_Roman_Emperor).
*   [John FitzGerald, de facto 12th Earl of Desmond](/John_FitzGerald,_de_facto_12th_Earl_of_Desmond) (d. 1536): Brother of the 11th Earl, and paternal granduncle of [James FitzGerald, de jure 12th Earl of Desmond](/James_FitzGerald,_de_jure_12th_Earl_of_Desmond).
*   [James FitzGerald, de jure 12th Earl of Desmond](/James_FitzGerald,_de_jure_12th_Earl_of_Desmond) (d. 1540): Grandson of [Thomas FitzGerald, 11th Earl of Desmond](/Thomas_FitzGerald,_11th_Earl_of_Desmond) and grandnephew of [John FitzGerald, de facto 12th Earl of Desmond](/John_FitzGerald,_de_facto_12th_Earl_of_Desmond).
*   [James FitzGerald, 13th Earl of Desmond](/James_FitzGerald,_13th_Earl_of_Desmond) (d. 1558): Son of [John FitzGerald, de facto 12th Earl of Desmond](/John_FitzGerald,_de_facto_12th_Earl_of_Desmond), he was appointed [Lord Treasurer of Ireland](/Lord_Treasurer_of_Ireland) by King [Edward VI](/Edward_VI).
*   [Gerald FitzGerald, 14th Earl of Desmond](/Gerald_FitzGerald,_14th_Earl_of_Desmond) (c. 1533–1583): Son of the 13th Earl, he was attainted in 1582. He fought in the [Battle of Affane](/Battle_of_Affane) and led the [Second Desmond Rebellion](/Second_Desmond_Rebellion).

The 16th Earl of Desmond, appointed by Hugh O'Neill (1598–1601).

*   [James FitzThomas FitzGerald](/James_FitzThomas_FitzGerald): Known as the Sugán Earl, he died in the [Tower of London](/Tower_of_London) around 1607. He was pursued by [George Carew, 1st Earl of Totnes](/George_Carew,_1st_Earl_of_Totnes).

**Earls of Desmond, Second Creation (1600)**

[Newnham Paddox House](/Monks_Kirby), the seat of the Earls of Desmond and later the [Earls of Denbigh](/Earls_of_Denbigh) since 1433, the title passing through the female line. It was granted to [Richard Preston, 1st Earl of Desmond](/Richard_Preston,_1st_Earl_of_Desmond).

*   [James FitzGerald, 1st Earl of Desmond](/James_FitzGerald,_1st_Earl_of_Desmond) (1571–1601): Known as the "Tower Earl of Desmond," he was the son of [Eleanor Butler, Countess of Desmond](/Eleanor_Butler,_Countess_of_Desmond).

**Lords of Decies**

*   [Gerald Fitzgerald, 3rd Lord Decies](/Gerald_Fitzgerald,_3rd_Lord_Decies): He married a daughter of [Piers Butler, 8th Earl of Ormond](/Piers_Butler,_8th_Earl_of_Ormond), a member of the prominent [House of Butler](/Butler_dynasty).

**FitzMaurice of Kerry**

[Cliveden House](/Cliveden_House), an estate once owned by Countess [FitzMaurice](/Mary_FitzMaurice,_4th_Countess_of_Orkney), sister-in-law to Prime Minister [Lord Shelburne](/Lord_Shelburne), Marquess of Lansdowne.

The closely related FitzMaurice Barons and later [Earls of Kerry](/Earls_of_Kerry) continue in the male line with the current Petty-FitzMaurice [Marquesses of Lansdowne](/Marquesses_of_Lansdowne). However, they descend from Thomas FitzMaurice, 1st Baron of Kerry, who was the nephew of [John FitzGerald, 1st Baron Desmond](/John_FitzGerald,_1st_Baron_Desmond). This makes them, technically, a "sister" branch to the FitzGeralds of Desmond. It also places them slightly closer to the FitzGeralds of Desmond than either are to the Offaly-Kildare-Leinster Geraldines, who are represented by the modern [Dukes of Leinster](/Dukes_of_Leinster) and descend from [Gerald FitzMaurice, 1st Lord of Offaly](/Gerald_FitzMaurice,_1st_Lord_of_Offaly), an uncle of the 1st Baron Desmond.

##### House of Corsygedol

The House of Corsygedol ([Vaughans](/House_of_Mathrafal)) is a cadet branch of the [Lords of Desmond](/Baron_Desmond), and later the [Earls of Desmond](/Earls_of_Desmond). It was established by [Osborn Wyddel](/Osborn_Wyddel) (Fitzgerald-Osbourne), a descendant of [Gerald de Windsor](/Gerald_de_Windsor). Wyddel arrived in [Wales](/Wales) (specifically the [Kingdom of Gwynedd](/Kingdom_of_Gwynedd)) from Ireland around the 13th century, accompanying Prince [Llywelyn the Great](/Llywelyn_the_Great). He was granted estates and arms, and married a ward of Llywelyn, who was also an heiress to the [Corsygedol](/Richard_Vaughan_(of_Corsygedol)) and [Plas Hen](/Talhenbont_hall) estates in [Gwynedd](/Gwynedd). This branch flourished in [North Wales](/North_Wales) for centuries. By the 18th century, their Corsygedol estates were inherited by the [Mostyn baronets](/Mostyn_baronets) family through marriage.

Its cadet branches include the [House of Yale](/Yale_(surname)) (Yale family) of Plas-yn-[Yale](/Ial) and the [Hughes of Gwerclas](/Hughes_of_Gwerclas) of [Gwerclas](/Gwerclas), both native royal families of the [Mathrafal dynasty](/House_of_Mathrafal). Their coat of arms is that of Osborn Fitzgerald: ermine on a saltire gules, a crescent or. The crest is a wild boar in a toil.

#### Hereditary Knights

The Earls of Desmond, acting as [Earls Palatine](/Earls_Palatine), established three [hereditary knighthoods](/Hereditary_knighthood) for their kinsmen.

*   [Knight of Kerry](/Knight_of_Kerry) (Green Knight): The current holder is Sir [Adrian FitzGerald](/Adrian_FitzGerald), 6th Baronet of Valencia, and the 24th Knight of Kerry. He is also a [Knight of Malta](/Sovereign_Military_Order_of_Malta) and President of the Irish Association of the [Sovereign Military Order of Malta](/Sovereign_Military_Order_of_Malta).
*   [Knight of Glin](/Knight_of_Glin) (Black Knight): This title is currently dormant (since 2011), following the death of [Desmond FitzGerald, 29th Knight of Glin](/Desmond_FitzGerald,_29th_Knight_of_Glin). The ancestral seat for over 700 years was [Glin Castle](/Glin_Castle).
*   [White Knight (Fitzgibbon family)](/White_Knight_(Fitzgibbon_family)): This title is also dormant (since 1611), following the death of Maurice Oge Fitzgibbon, the 12th White Knight.

#### Legacy

The surname Fitzgerald/FitzGerald, according to the 1890 Matheson report, was the 36th most common surname in Ireland.

In the United Kingdom, Fitzgerald/FitzGerald ranks as the 692nd most frequent surname. It appears most commonly in the following ten counties: Greater London (500 occurrences), Greater Manchester (191), West Midlands (176), Lancashire (130), Kent (118), Essex (117), West Yorkshire (113), Merseyside (108), Hampshire (84), and Surrey (76).

In the United States, "Fitzgerald" (including "FitzGerald," as the survey was not case-sensitive) was the 390th most common surname in the 2000 census. A total of 73,522 individuals bore the name Fitzgerald, representing 27.25 per 100,000 members of the population. Of those surveyed, 88.03% identified as non-Hispanic white, 8.44% as non-Hispanic black, 0.32% as non-Hispanic Asian or Pacific Islander, 1.28% as non-Hispanic Asian, 1.43% as belonging to two or more non-Hispanic races, and 1.43% identified as Hispanic.

The FitzGerald dynasty was the subject of the poem "The Geraldines" by [Thomas Osborne Davis](/Thomas_Davis_(Young_Irelander)), a leading figure and poet of the nationalist [Young Ireland](/Young_Ireland) movement. The tragic romance between [Thomas FitzGerald, 5th Earl of Desmond](/Thomas_FitzGerald,_5th_Earl_of_Desmond) and Catherine MacCormac inspired the air "Desmond's Song" by the Irish poet [Thomas Moore](/Thomas_Moore).

The [Saint Patrick's Saltire](/Saint_Patrick%27s_Saltire), sometimes incorporated into modern Irish flags, may have its origins in the coat of arms of the Geraldines.

The Arleigh Burke-class destroyer USS Fitzgerald in the [United States Navy](/United_States_Navy) is named in honor of Lieutenant [William Charles Fitzgerald](/William_Charles_Fitzgerald), USN. The FitzGerald family coat of arms, a white shield with a red saltire, forms the basis for the coat of arms of the USS Fitzgerald.

A variety of [people, places, and businesses](/FitzGerald_(disambiguation)) bear the FitzGerald or Fitzgerald name. Notably, the [FitzGerald crater](/Fitz_Gerald_(crater)) on the far side of the [Moon](/Moon) is named after the physicist [George FitzGerald](/George_Francis_FitzGerald).

